Introduction

In this markdown, we analyze data of collegiate Sports Budgets.

Click here to watch the data

Goals

Our research will focus on two main questions:

  • Is there a correlation between the amount invested in the sports branches and the revenue they achieved?

  • Is there a difference between the investments per individual in public and private collages?

Data import

The data set is taken from Tidytuesday and comes in a CSV file.

Let’s read this file with read.csv function that imports the data into R.

sports <- readr::read_csv('https://raw.githubusercontent.com/rfordatascience/tidytuesday/master/data/2022/2022-03-29/sports.csv')

Data Dictionary

variable class description
year integer year, which is year: year + 1, eg 2015 is 2015 to 2016
unitid double School ID
institution_name character School name
city_txt character City name
state_cd character State abbreviation
zip_text character Zip of school
classification_code double Code for school classification
classification_name character School classification
classification_other character School classification other
ef_male_count double Total male student
ef_female_count double Total Female student
ef_total_count double Total student for binary male/female gender (sum of previous two cols)
sector_cd double Sector code
sector_name character Sector name
sportscode double Sport code
partic_men double Participation men
partic_women double Participation women
partic_coed_men double Participation as coed men
partic_coed_women double Participation for coed women
sum_partic_men double Sum of participation for men
sum_partic_women double Sum of participation women
rev_men double Revenue in USD for men
rev_women double Revenue in USD for women
total_rev_menwomen double Total revenue for both
exp_men double Expenditures in USD for men
exp_women double Expenditures in USD for women
total_exp_menwomen double Total Expenditure for both
sports character Sport name

Tidying

First, we will make some changes, by adding a column of the male and female participants combined.

Also, we will change the NA values to zeroes in certain columns that should contain numerical values only, so the data will be more capable to work with.

sports<-sports%>%
  mutate(total_partic=partic_men+partic_women)

sports<-sports%>%
  relocate(total_partic, .after = sum_partic_women)

sports$total_partic[is.na(sports$total_partic)] <- 0
sports$partic_women[is.na(sports$partic_women)] <- 0
sports$partic_men[is.na(sports$partic_men)] <- 0
sports$rev_men[is.na(sports$rev_men)] <- 0
sports$rev_women[is.na(sports$rev_women)] <- 0
sports$exp_men[is.na(sports$exp_men)] <- 0
sports$exp_women[is.na(sports$exp_women)] <- 0
sports$total_rev_menwomen[is.na(sports$total_rev_menwomen)] <- 0
sports$total_exp_menwomen[is.na(sports$total_exp_menwomen)] <- 0

In our project, we will concentrate in the familiar classifications only, so we will get rid of the rows, where the classification name is “Other” or “Independent”.

sports <- subset (sports, select = -c(classification_other,partic_coed_men,partic_coed_women))
sports<-sports[!(sports$classification_name=="Other"|sports$classification_name=="Independent"),]

Visualizations

Let’s get started!

First, we will show the distribution of collages expenses over the years invested in sports:

total_expense_distribution<-ggplot(data=sports, aes(x=total_exp_menwomen))+
  geom_density(fill="lavenderblush")+
  scale_x_log10(labels = dollar_format(prefix = "$"))
total_expense_distribution+ggtitle("Total expense distribution")

As we can see, the amount of expenses on men and women combined distribute almost normally.

EXPENSES OVER THE YEARS

Next, we will show expenses on the variety of sports over the years:

total_expense_by_year<-sports%>%
  group_by(year)%>%
  summarize(total_expense=sum(total_exp_menwomen))
total_expense_by_year<-ggplot(data = total_expense_by_year) + 
  geom_smooth(mapping = aes(x = year, y = total_expense))+
  scale_y_log10(labels = dollar_format(prefix = "$"))
total_expense_by_year+ ggtitle("Total expense by year")

From the chart we can learn that the amount of investments raised between 2015 to 2018, and since 2018 slightly decreased (until 2019).

TOP 5

Now, let’s see on which sports branches collages invest the most!

most_invested <- sports%>%

most_invested<-most_invested[rev(order(most_invested[,2])),]%>%

top_5<-most_invested[1:5]

expense_by_gender<-sports%>%

NCAA

NCAA - The National Collegiate Athletic Association is a member-led organization dedicated to the well-being and lifelong success of college athletes, and considered as the best league to take part in the USA.

We want to concentrate in the leagues divisions with football in the NCAA, and check the connection between the number of participants and the revenues by men and women.

ncaa<-sports%>%
  select(classification_name,partic_men,rev_men,partic_women,rev_women)%>%
filter(classification_name==c("NCAA Division I-FBS","NCAA Division II with football","NCAA Division III with football"))
leagues_men<-ggplot(ncaa, aes(x=partic_men, y=rev_men,colour=classification_name))+
scale_y_log10(labels = dollar_format(prefix = "$")) +
  geom_point() 
leagues_women<-ggplot(ncaa, aes(x=partic_women, y=rev_women,colour=classification_name))+
scale_y_log10(labels = dollar_format(prefix = "$")) +
  geom_point() 
grid.arrange(leagues_men+ggtitle("Revenue - men")+ scale_color_brewer(palette="Set1"),leagues_women+ggtitle("Revenue - women")+ scale_color_brewer(palette="Set1"))

There are a lot of conclusions we can learn from those charts:

  • First, in NCAA division 1 the profits are highest, and as we go down by divisions level, the profits decrease.

  • Second, the number of participants is not a factor to the revenues - what matter is the league itself.

  • Third, in here we can see the differences between men and women - the profits of men are up to 100M dollars, and of women are up to 10M dollars (maybe because women are less invested as we have seen above…)

Also, the box plot shows us that in top 5 sports, as the various of participants decreases , the median of number of participants decreases.

Modeling

Let’s start with the interesting stuff!

First-model

We will check if there is a correlation between the amount of expenses and revenues.

exp_rev<-sports%>%
  group_by(sports)%>%
  summarize(tot_sum_revenue=sum(total_rev_menwomen),tot_sum_expenses=sum(total_exp_menwomen))%>%
  mutate(profit=tot_sum_revenue-tot_sum_expenses)

Hypothesis

Our null hypothesis is that expense and revenue are not correlated - every sport branch has his own profit or losses and the general connection is not permanent .

exp_rev_corr<-lm(formula =log1p(tot_sum_expenses)~log1p(tot_sum_revenue), data= exp_rev)
summary(exp_rev_corr)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = log1p(tot_sum_expenses) ~ log1p(tot_sum_revenue), 
##     data = exp_rev)
##

## F-statistic:  8667 on 1 and 36 DF,  p-value: < 2.2e-16
regresion<-exp_rev%>% 
ggplot(aes(y=tot_sum_revenue, x=tot_sum_expenses))+
  geom_point(color="seagreen3")+
  scale_y_log10(labels = dollar_format(prefix = "$"))+
  scale_x_log10(labels = dollar_format(prefix = "$"))+
  stat_smooth(method = "lm",color="black")
regresion+ggtitle("The correlation between expenses and revenues")

As we can see the p-value is significantly lower than 0.05, so in contrary to our expectation, there is a correlation between the expenses and the revenues .

The R squared is above 99 percents so the correlation is very strong, almost identical, although the information in exp_rev table shows us that there are some big differences - the connection between investments and revenues is changing in different sports branches.

Second model

Now we will move to our next question - is there a difference between the investment in public and private collages?

We will start from building a table that will have the revenue by person, and a Boolean column that will help us to separate between public and private collages.

sectors<-sports%>%
  filter(year==2015)%>%
  group_by(institution_name,sector_name)%>%
  summarise(tot_part_man=sum(sum_partic_men),tot_part_woman=sum(sum_partic_women)
  ,tot_exp=sum(total_exp_menwomen),sum_exp_men=sum(exp_men)
  ,sum_exp_women=sum(exp_women))%>%
  mutate(women_exp_mean=(sum_exp_women/tot_part_woman))%>%
  mutate(man_exp_mean=(sum_exp_men/tot_part_man))%>%
  mutate(exp_mean_by_person=tot_exp/(tot_part_woman+tot_part_man))%>%
  mutate(is_public=str_detect(sector_name,"Public"))

Let’s start from showing the distributions of public and private collages expense mean:

public_exp<-sectors%>%
  filter(is_public)

public_exp$man_exp_mean[is.nan(public_exp$man_exp_mean)] <- 0
public_exp$women_exp_mean[is.nan(public_exp$women_exp_mean)] <- 0

public_exp_mean_by_person<-ggplot(data=public_exp, aes(x=exp_mean_by_person))+
  scale_x_log10(labels = dollar_format(prefix = "$"))+
  geom_density(fill="orange")+
  coord_cartesian(ylim=c(0,1))
private_exp<-sectors%>%
  filter(!is_public)

private_exp$man_exp_mean[is.nan(private_exp$man_exp_mean)] <- 0
private_exp$women_exp_mean[is.nan(private_exp$women_exp_mean)] <- 0

private_exp_mean_by_person<-ggplot(data=private_exp, aes(x=exp_mean_by_person))+
  scale_x_log10(labels = dollar_format(prefix = "$"))+
  geom_density(fill="beige")
grid.arrange(private_exp_mean_by_person+ggtitle("Private expense mean by person"),
             public_exp_mean_by_person+ggtitle("Public expense mean by person")
             ,ncol=2)

So, as we can see there are two “humps” is these distributions. A possible explanation is the difference of means for the women and men.

Let’s find the means and see if there are differences.

private_women_exp_mean<-mean(private_exp$women_exp_mean)
private_men_exp_mean<-mean(private_exp$man_exp_mean)
public_women_exp_mean<-mean(public_exp$women_exp_mean)
public_men_exp_mean<-mean(public_exp$man_exp_mean)

Private school expense on women mean:

private_women_exp_mean
## [1] 11126.6

private_men_exp_mean
## [1] 12777.54

Public school expense on women mean:

public_women_exp_mean
## [1] 12166.67

Public school expense on men mean:

public_men_exp_mean
## [1] 17117.6

As we Assumed, there are differences between men and women means.

Next thing we are going to do is a T test to check if there is a difference between private and public collages investments per person:

t.test(private_exp$exp_mean_by_person,public_exp$exp_mean_by_person)
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  private_exp$exp_mean_by_person and public_exp$exp_mean_by_person
## t = -3.3088, df = 1952.1, p-value = 0.000954
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -4226.932 -1080.891
## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
##  11938.17  14592.08

Our null hypothesis was that there isn’t a difference in the investments in public and private collages. As we can see in the t-test above, the p-value is 0.000954, so we can say in significance level of 0.05 that there is a difference, so we do reject the null hypothesis.

In addition, the mean of investments in public collages is bigger than the private collages investments mean per person - and if we take a look in the comparison between men and women that showed above, we will see the public mean per person is bigger thanks to investment in women (we are still in shock…)

Conclusions

We checked two main questions -

  • Is there a correlation between the amount of total investments in the sport branches and the total revenues they achieved?

  • Is there a difference between the investments per individual in public and private collages?

The first model showed a strong correlation between the two variables, even though the connection between investments and revenues is not permanent in every sport branch.

The second model reviled that there are differences in the investments in public and private collages, and surprisingly,participants in public collages are more invested!
